<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="section-1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Infinite Series</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This section is about infinite series. We will mainly focus on presenting the 
      definitions and providing some examples such as the geometric series.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-definitions">
    <title>Basic Definitions</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-sequence">
      <statement>
        <p>A sequence is a list of numbers <m>a_0, a_1, a_2, \ldots</m> 
        indexed by the natural numbers.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
 
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-1">
    <title>Partial Sums</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-partial-sum">
      <statement>
        <p>The sum of the first <m> n </m> terms in a sequence is denoted by <m> S_n </m> and it is known as a partial sum.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <example xml:id="example-geometric-series">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the sum of the geometric series <m> \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{4} + \frac{1}{8} + \cdots</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Since this is a geometric series with first term <m>a = \frac{1}{2}</m> and ratio <m>r = \frac{1}{2}</m>, the sum is:
        <me>S_n =\sum_{i=0}^n a_i=\frac{a}{1-r} = \frac{\frac{1}{2}}{1-\frac{1}{2}} = 1</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <figure>
      <caption>Visual Example of a Geometric Series</caption>
      <image source="fig1.pdf" width="40%">
        <description>
          <p>The sum of areas of the rectangles represents the 
          partial sum of the geometric series.
          </p>
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </subsection>
</section>